Test Data: How do migrant workers contribute to the economy of their host countries?
Generated Result: Migrant workers contribute to the economy of their host countries in several ways. They are often willing to accept lower wages than local workers, which can help companies reduce labor costs. Migrant workers are also willing to do work that the local workforce may not be willing to do, such as jobs in remote areas or industries with labor shortages. Additionally, migrant workers may have specialized skills that are in demand and not readily available among the local workforce. Their contributions can lead to increased productivity, higher salaries, greater mobility for workers, and more exposure and skills for future opportunities.
